<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <br>
A paladin is the very embodiment of a holy knight, *FIGHTING FOR THE CAUSE OF GOOD* in every aspect of his or her life. As the paladin gains life experience and proves his devotion, he will be granted the ability to use limited clerical magics. They share some of the powers of clerics along with a good deal of the fighting ability of warriors, but have a few virtues all their own. Only those who are pure in heart can become paladins, and the so-called &quot;evil&quot; races have yet to produce them. Dwarves, Erudites, half elves, high elves and humans are the only races that count them among their numbers. <br>
</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
(Emphasis mine)<br>
<br>
This is why there are no Paladins of Innoruuk or Cazic-Thule, and why there SHOULDN'T be any Paladins of Brell or Bristlebane. (Okay, I'll let Brell pass...<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
Generally, this just leads to debates about the definition of &quot;good.&quot;<br>
<br>
There's still a lot of leeway though, such as whether or not you must heal everyone who needs it, how bloodthirsty you are when it comes to evil beings, and the like. Some Paladins may view other PCs as distractions to his quest to slay evil, and totally ignore a human being killed by a bear. They can be condescending and even rude, and still fit the description well enough. Personally, I try to be as humble as a High Elf can be. (But it's hard when you're just so damn suave.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
I think that a Paladin's chosen deity (or in some cases, the deity that chose them) affects how they act, but doesn't change their behavior drastically. For example, a Paladin of Brell may not mind helping out someone in a losing battle with a wolf, while a Paladin of Tunare might be a little more hesitant.<br>
<br>
