<br>
Historically, the term &quot;paladin&quot; refers to a &quot;palace guard.&quot; It's primary meaning descends from the stories of Charlamagne and his 12 &quot;peers&quot; or companions. They were noble &quot;chevaliers&quot; or &quot;cavaliers&quot; - the most loyal, fierce knights of the French king.<br>
<br>
The most famous of the 12 peers was Roland, along with his closest friend Olivier (or Oliver). Roland was brutally honest and fiercely loyal. He wielded a magical blade (Durandal), had a &quot;magical&quot; horn and a very intelligent, loyal steed.<br>
<br>
Roland is pretty much the prototype or archetype of what we think of as a paladin, and his character included the Fatal Flaw which most mythological paladins (perhaps with the exception of Galahad) have. Roland's flaw or sin was Pride and the tale of his downfall (&quot;The Song of Roland&quot;) was the most famous stories of the peers.<br>
<br>
There are echoes of Roland in other famous knights, such as Lancelot. Pure, noble and brave... but with a flaw (in this case, love for a woman).<br>
<br>
Interestingly, it seems that the relationship between a paladin and his deity wasn't an essential part of paladin-hood until Dungeons &amp; Dragons incorporated it. Prior to that, a paladin was considered holy in the sense that he remained pure and devoted, but his devotion was to King, not primarily to God. Prior to D&amp;D, a paladin was much more like a samurai than a priest.<br>
<br>
D&amp;D, I think, drew a lot of inspiration from the Knights Templar and other religious orders of knights - who historically would not have been considered PALADINS, as they were NOT &quot;palace guards&quot; or part of of the royal entourage.<br>
<br>
Most dictionaries are now much more ambigious about the meaning of the term and typically define a paladin as a martial person devoted to a cause. Religion might be the cause, but it could also be political or generically moral in nature. The Lone Ranger, for example, is very much a paladin in modern terms but he was not specifically religious.<br>
<br>
Outside of people familiar with RPGs (either pencil &amp; paper or CRPGs) the term &quot;paladin&quot; has become mostly meaningless. If you ask 100 people to describe a paladin, probably fewer than 10 will be able to define the term. Those who do will frequently make reference to the old Western series named Paladin (&quot;'Have card, will travel' read the card of a man... a knight without armor in a lawless land...&quot;).<br>
<br>
I was drawn to the paladin archetype long before I knew the term paladin. I started playing D&amp;D when I was around 12 or 13, but was a fan of characters like the Lone Ranger prior to having heard of the game. In fact, the first character I played was Romidar, whose name I based on &quot;Rom: Spaceknight,&quot; a comic book of the late 70's, early 80's period. (Rom had given up his humanity to become a cyborg and forever fight the thread of evil dire wraiths!)<br>
<br>
